# libGDX Headless Viewport Projection Pipeline

## Background
Games built with libGDX commonly use an `OrthographicCamera` paired with a `Viewport` (e.g., `FitViewport`, `ExtendViewport`, `StretchViewport`, `ScreenViewport`) so that the same world coordinates render consistently across many screen sizes. The headless backend ships with `MockGraphics`, so no real OpenGL context exists, but the math behind `Camera`/`Viewport`/`Vector3` is plain Java and runs perfectly under `HeadlessApplication`.

Your job is to build a deterministic CLI tool — `viewport-projector` — that boots libGDX's headless backend, replays a scripted sequence of window resize events and world points read from a JSON scenario file, and writes the resulting screen-space coordinates (and an unproject round-trip check) to an output log file. The tool will be used by an automated grader to validate viewport math without ever touching a GPU.

## Requirements
- Create a Gradle multi-module libGDX project under `/home/user/myproject` with a `core` module that contains the projection logic and a `headless` module that boots the headless backend.
- Pin libGDX to version `1.14.2` (`com.badlogicgames.gdx:gdx:1.14.2`, `com.badlogicgames.gdx:gdx-backend-headless:1.14.2`, `com.badlogicgames.gdx:gdx-platform:1.14.2:natives-desktop`).
- The headless module's launcher class must accept two command-line arguments: `--scenario=<path-to-json>` and `--output=<path-to-log>`.
- The launcher must boot `HeadlessApplication` with `HeadlessApplicationConfiguration.updatesPerSecond = 60` and run the scenario to completion before calling `Gdx.app.exit()`. The Java process must terminate cleanly (exit code 0) after the headless main-loop thread finishes.
- The scenario file is a JSON document with the following stable schema (parsed via libGDX's `com.badlogic.gdx.utils.Json`/`JsonReader` or any equivalent JSON library):
  ```json
  {
    "viewport": "fit" | "extend" | "stretch" | "screen",
    "worldWidth": <number>,
    "worldHeight": <number>,
    "cameraPosition": { "x": <number>, "y": <number> },
    "frames": [
      {
        "frame": <int>,
        "resize": { "width": <int>, "height": <int> },
        "points": [ { "x": <number>, "y": <number> } ]
      }
    ]
  }
  ```
  - `viewport` selects which `Viewport` subclass to instantiate around an `OrthographicCamera`.
  - `worldWidth` / `worldHeight` are the virtual viewport dimensions passed to the viewport constructor. For `"screen"` the values are ignored.
  - `cameraPosition` sets `camera.position.x` / `camera.position.y` once during `create()` (z is always 0).
  - Each entry of `frames` describes one render tick. The launcher must process them in ascending `frame` order. When `resize` is present, call `viewport.update(width, height, true)` BEFORE projecting that frame's points. The `points` list (zero or more) contains world-space points to project.
- For every point in every frame, write exactly one line to the output log in the format:
  ```
  FRAME <frame> PROJECT (<wx>,<wy>) -> (<sx>,<sy>)
  ```
  where `<wx>`, `<wy>`, `<sx>`, `<sy>` are formatted with `String.format(java.util.Locale.US, "%.3f", value)` (three decimals, US locale, dot decimal separator, no thousands separator). `<sx>`/`<sy>` are computed via `viewport.project(new Vector2(wx, wy))`.
- After processing all frames, write one round-trip line per `(frame, point)` pair, in the same order as the PROJECT lines, using the LAST applied viewport size:
  ```
  ROUNDTRIP <frame> (<wx>,<wy>) -> (<rx>,<ry>) <STATUS>
  ```
  where `<rx>`/`<ry>` come from `viewport.unproject(viewport.project(point))` (run on a fresh `Vector2` each time) and `<STATUS>` is the literal string `OK` if `|rx - wx| <= 0.01 && |ry - wy| <= 0.01`, otherwise `MISMATCH`. Use the same `%.3f` formatting for the numbers.
- After the last ROUNDTRIP line, write a final line:
  ```
  END frames=<N> points=<M>
  ```
  where `<N>` is the number of frames processed and `<M>` is the total number of points projected.
- The launcher MUST NOT print any other lines to the output file. Diagnostic messages to stdout/stderr are allowed and ignored by the grader.
- The tool must be invocable from the project root with:
  ```bash
  ./gradlew --no-daemon --console=plain headless:run --args="--scenario=<abs-path> --output=<abs-path>"
  ```
  Each invocation must overwrite (not append to) the output file.

## Implementation Hints
- Use `gradle wrapper --gradle-version 8.10 --distribution-type bin` to bootstrap the Gradle wrapper non-interactively.
- A clean way to organise the project is `core` (contains a `ProjectionApp` implementing `ApplicationAdapter`) and `headless` (contains a `HeadlessLauncher` `main` method that parses args, loads the scenario, instantiates `ProjectionApp`, and starts `HeadlessApplication`). Keep all `OpenGL`-touching code out of the headless path — `OrthographicCamera`, `Vector2`, and the `Viewport` math do not need a GL context.
- The headless module needs an `application` plugin configuration with `mainClass` set to the launcher, and `run.standardInput = System.in`, so that `./gradlew headless:run --args=...` works.
- `Viewport.project` and `Viewport.unproject` both mutate their input `Vector2`; create a fresh vector for every call so logs stay deterministic.
- Call `viewport.update(width, height, true)` (note the `centerCamera = true` flag) the first time before any projection (e.g., inside `create()` with a sensible default like the scenario's first `resize`), and again whenever a frame supplies a new `resize`. Without an initial `update`, `Viewport.project` returns NaN because the screen size is still 0.
- Use `Gdx.app.postRunnable(() -> Gdx.app.exit())` after the last frame so the main loop drains cleanly. Join the main-loop thread (`((HeadlessApplication) Gdx.app).getApplicationListener()` is just `ProjectionApp`; the thread is `"HeadlessApplication"`) from `HeadlessLauncher` before exiting `main`.
- When formatting numbers, ALWAYS pass `java.util.Locale.US` to `String.format`; the grader compares strings literally.

## Acceptance Criteria
- Project path: `/home/user/myproject`
- Command: `./gradlew --no-daemon --console=plain headless:run --args="--scenario=<abs-scenario.json> --output=<abs-output.log>"` run from `/home/user/myproject`.
- Arguments:
  - `--scenario=<path>`: absolute path to a JSON scenario file matching the schema above.
  - `--output=<path>`: absolute path to the log file. Any existing file at this path is overwritten on every invocation.
- libGDX coordinates: `gdx`, `gdx-backend-headless`, and `gdx-platform:natives-desktop`, all pinned to `1.14.2`.
- The Gradle command must exit with status `0` once the scenario completes.
- Output log format (all numbers formatted as `%.3f` using `java.util.Locale.US`):
  - One `FRAME <frame> PROJECT (<wx>,<wy>) -> (<sx>,<sy>)` line per scenario point, in the order frames appear in the input and in the order points appear within a frame.
  - After all PROJECT lines, one `ROUNDTRIP <frame> (<wx>,<wy>) -> (<rx>,<ry>) <STATUS>` line per scenario point (same order), where `<STATUS>` is `OK` or `MISMATCH` using the `0.01` tolerance described in Requirements.
  - Exactly one trailing `END frames=<N> points=<M>` line.
  - No additional lines beyond the structure above.
- Empty `points` arrays must produce no PROJECT/ROUNDTRIP lines for that frame but must still count toward `<N>`.
- The `<sx>`/`<sy>` values must match the result of `viewport.project(new Vector2(wx, wy))` after the most recent `viewport.update(width, height, true)` call for that frame.


