# libGDX Headless Lifecycle Frame Counter

## Background
libGDX is a cross-platform Java game-development framework. Its headless back-end (`gdx-backend-headless`) drives an `ApplicationListener` lifecycle without an OpenGL context, which makes it suitable for CI runs, server-side simulations, and lifecycle assertions. In this task you will build a small Gradle project that boots a libGDX `HeadlessApplication`, ticks for a configurable number of render frames, and shuts down cleanly while reporting how many frames were rendered.

## Requirements
- Implement an `ApplicationListener` (or `ApplicationAdapter` subclass) that:
  - Initializes a frame counter to zero in `create()`.
  - Increments the counter on every `render()` invocation.
  - Calls `Gdx.app.exit()` once the counter has reached the target tick count `N`.
  - On `dispose()`, prints a single line `FRAME_COUNT: <N>` to standard output (using `Gdx.app.log` or `System.out.println`).
- Provide a `Main` launcher class that reads the integer argument `N` from the command line, constructs a `HeadlessApplicationConfiguration` (with a deterministic `updatesPerSecond`), starts a `HeadlessApplication`, waits for the headless main loop thread to finish, and then exits with code `0`.
- The Gradle build must declare a real dependency on `com.badlogicgames.gdx:gdx-backend-headless` (and the core `com.badlogicgames.gdx:gdx`) for libGDX `1.14.2`, configure a `JavaExec` task named `run` whose `mainClass`/`main` is the launcher, and pass the command-line argument through to the JVM via Gradle's `--args` mechanism.
- Provide an executable shell script `run.sh` in the project root that takes a single positional integer argument `N` and runs the headless application via `./gradlew --no-daemon -q run --args="$N"`. The script must succeed (exit code 0) and stream the program's standard output to its own standard output.

## Implementation Hints
- The headless back-end is documented at the [libGDX Life Cycle page](https://libgdx.com/wiki/app/the-life-cycle) and the [`HeadlessApplication` source](https://github.com/libgdx/libgdx/blob/master/backends/gdx-backend-headless/src/com/badlogic/gdx/backends/headless/HeadlessApplication.java). Setting `HeadlessApplicationConfiguration.updatesPerSecond` controls the tick cadence; choose a value high enough (for example `1000`) so the test does not stall.
- `HeadlessApplication` runs the main loop on its own `Thread` named `"HeadlessApplication"`. After construction, retrieve that thread and `join()` it from the launcher so the process does not exit before `dispose()` runs.
- `Gdx.app.exit()` posts a runnable that flips `running=false`; the listener's `dispose()` will be invoked at the end of the loop.
- Use `com.badlogicgames.gdx:gdx:1.14.2` and `com.badlogicgames.gdx:gdx-backend-headless:1.14.2` from Maven Central. The `gdx-platform:1.14.2:natives-desktop` artifact is not required when only the headless back-end is used, but you may include it if your build needs it.
- Make sure stdout for the `run.sh` invocation is clean: configure Gradle (or the `JavaExec` task) so that only your program's output reaches stdout. `--quiet` (`-q`) on Gradle and `standardOutput`/`errorOutput` wiring on the `JavaExec` task are enough.

## Acceptance Criteria
- Project path: /home/user/myproject
- Command: `bash run.sh <N>`
- Command input argument format: a single positional integer `N` (the number of render frames before exit), `1 <= N <= 1000`.
- Expected command output format:
  - The standard output of `bash run.sh <N>` must contain a line matching exactly `FRAME_COUNT: <N>` (no leading or trailing whitespace on that line).
  - The command must exit with status code `0`.
- The Gradle build must declare `com.badlogicgames.gdx:gdx-backend-headless:1.14.2` as a dependency, and the application must actually boot via `com.badlogic.gdx.backends.headless.HeadlessApplication`.
- The application must call `Gdx.app.exit()` from its own `ApplicationListener` (i.e., the lifecycle is driven by the listener, not by an external timer killing the JVM).


